[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A differential equation that is not linear.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A number of coupled differential equations form a system of equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] is an *explicit system of ordinary differential equations* of *order* n and *dimension* m .
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] In the same sources, implicit ODE systems with a singular Jacobian are termed differential algebraic equations (DAEs).
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] This distinction is not merely one of terminology; DAEs have fundamentally different characteristics and are generally more involved to solve than (nonsingular) ODE systems.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The behavior of a system of ODEs can be visualized through the use of a phase portrait.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A solution that has no extension is called a *maximal solution*.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A solution defined on all of $\mathbb {R}$ is called a *global solution*.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A *general solution* of an n th-order equation is a solution containing n arbitrary independent constants of integration.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A *particular solution* is derived from the general solution by setting the constants to particular values, often chosen to fulfill set 'initial conditions or boundary conditions'.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A singular solution is a solution that cannot be obtained by assigning definite values to the arbitrary constants in the general solution.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] This is the terminology used in the guessing method section in this article, and is frequently used when discussing the method of undetermined coefficients and variation of parameters.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] For non-linear autonomous ODEs it is possible under some conditions to develop solutions of finite duration, meaning here that from its own dynamics, the system will reach the value zero at an ending time and stays there in zero forever after.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] These finite-duration solutions can't be analytical functions on the whole real line, and because they will be non-Lipschitz functions at their ending time, they are not included in the uniqueness theorem of solutions of Lipschitz differential equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The theory of singular solutions of ordinary and partial differential equations was a subject of research from the time of Leibniz, but only since the middle of the nineteenth century has it received special attention.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A valuable but little-known work on the subject is that of Houtain (1854).
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Darboux (from 1873) was a leader in the theory, and in the geometric interpretation of these solutions he opened a field worked by various writers, notably Casorati and Cayley.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] To the latter is due (1872) the theory of singular solutions of differential equations of the first order as accepted circa 1900.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The primitive attempt in dealing with differential equations had in view a reduction to quadratures, that is, expressing the solutions in terms of known function and their integrals.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] This is possible for linear equations with constant coefficients, it appeared in the 19th century that this is generally impossible in other cases.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Hence, analysts began the study (for their own) of functions that are solutions of differential equations, thus opening a new and fertile field.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Cauchy was the first to appreciate the importance of this view.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Thereafter, the real question was no longer whether a solution is possible by quadratures, but whether a given differential equation suffices for the definition of a function, and, if so, what are the characteristic properties of such functions.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Two memoirs by Fuchs inspired a novel approach, subsequently elaborated by Thomé and Frobenius.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] (WHO?)Collet was a prominent contributor beginning in 1869.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] His method for integrating a non-linear system was communicated to Bertrand in 1868.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Clebsch (1873) attacked the theory along lines parallel to those in his theory of Abelian integrals.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] From 1870, Sophus Lie's work put the theory of differential equations on a better foundation.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] He showed that the integration theories of the older mathematicians can, using Lie groups, be referred to a common source, and that ordinary differential equations that admit the same infinitesimal transformations present comparable integration difficulties.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] He also emphasized the subject of transformations of contact.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Lie's group theory of differential equations has been certified, namely: (1) that it unifies the many ad hoc methods known for solving differential equations, and (2) that it provides powerful new ways to find solutions.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The theory has applications to both ordinary and partial differential equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] A general solution approach uses the symmetry property of differential equations, the continuous infinitesimal transformations of solutions to solutions (Lie theory).
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Symmetry methods have been applied to differential equations that arise in mathematics, physics, engineering, and other disciplines.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Sturm–Liouville theory is a theory of a special type of second-order linear ordinary differential equation.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Their solutions are based on eigenvalues and corresponding eigenfunctions of linear operators defined via second-order homogeneous linear equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The problems are identified as Sturm–Liouville problems (SLP) and are named after J.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Liouville, who studied them in the mid-1800s.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] SLPs have an infinite number of eigenvalues, and the corresponding eigenfunctions form a complete, orthogonal set, which makes orthogonal expansions possible.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] This is a key idea in applied mathematics, physics, and engineering.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] SLPs are also useful in the analysis of certain partial differential equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] There are several theorems that establish existence and uniqueness of solutions to initial value problems involving ODEs both locally and globally.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] In their basic form both of these theorems only guarantee local results, though the latter can be extended to give a global result, for example, if the conditions of Grönwall's inequality are met.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Also, uniqueness theorems like the Lipschitz one above do not apply to DAE systems, which may have multiple solutions stemming from their (non-linear) algebraic part alone.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The theorem can be stated simply as follows.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] That is, there is a solution and it is unique.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Since there is no restriction on F to be linear, this applies to non-linear equations that take the form $F(x,y)$ , and it can also be applied to systems of equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] When the hypotheses of the Picard–Lindelöf theorem are satisfied, then local existence and uniqueness can be extended to a global result.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] such that any solution that satisfies this initial condition is a restriction of the solution that satisfies this initial condition with domain $I_{\max }$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] where $\Omega$ is the open set in which F is defined, and $\partial {\bar {\Omega }}$ is its boundary.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] This means that $F(x,y)=y^{2}$ , which is $C^{1}$ and therefore locally Lipschitz continuous, satisfying the Picard–Lindelöf theorem.
