[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Differential equations are usually easier to solve if the order of the equation can be reduced.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Some differential equations have solutions that can be written in an exact and closed form.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] Several important classes are given here.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] In the table below, $P(x)$ , $Q(x)$ , $P(y)$ , $Q(y)$ , and $M(x,y)$ , $N(x,y)$ are any integrable functions of x , y ; b and c are real given constants; $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ are arbitrary constants (complex in general).
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] The differential equations are in their equivalent and alternative forms that lead to the solution through integration.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] When all other methods for solving an ODE fail, or in the cases where we have some intuition about what the solution to a DE might look like, it is sometimes possible to solve a DE simply by guessing the solution and validating it is correct.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] To use this method, we simply guess a solution to the differential equation, and then plug the solution into the differential equation to verify whether it satisfies the equation.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] If it does then we have a particular solution to the DE, otherwise we start over again and try another guess.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] For instance we could guess that the solution to a DE has the form: $y=Ae^{i\alpha t}$ since this is a very common solution that physically behaves in a sinusoidal way.
[src:differential-equations-ode/ordinary-differential-equation] In the case of a first order ODE that is non-homogeneous we need to first find a solution to the homogeneous portion of the DE, otherwise known as the associated homogeneous equation, and then find a solution to the entire non-homogeneous equation by guessing.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] In mathematics, specifically the study of differential equations, the **Picard–Lindelöf theorem** gives a set of sufficient (but not necessary) conditions under which an initial value problem has a unique solution.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] It is also known as **Picard's existence theorem**, the **Cauchy–Lipschitz theorem**, or the **existence and uniqueness theorem**.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The theorem is named after Émile Picard, Ernst Lindelöf, Rudolf Lipschitz and Augustin-Louis Cauchy.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] A standard proof relies on transforming the differential equation into an integral equation, then applying the Banach fixed-point theorem to prove the existence and uniqueness of solutions.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Given the hypotheses that f is continuous in t and Lipschitz continuous in y , this integral operator is a contraction (See detailed proof below) and so the Banach fixed-point theorem proves that a solution can be obtained by fixed-point iteration of successive approximations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] In this context, this fixed-point iteration method is known as Picard iteration.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Since the Banach fixed-point theorem states that the fixed-point is unique, the solution found through this iteration is the unique solution to the differential equation given an initial value.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] To understand uniqueness of solutions, contrast the following two examples of first order ordinary differential equations for *y*(*t*).
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Both differential equations will possess a single stationary point *y* = 0.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] First, the homogeneous linear equation ⁠*dy*/*dt*⁠ = *ay* ( $a<0$ ), a stationary solution is *y*(*t*) = 0, which is obtained for the initial condition *y*(0) = 0.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Beginning with any other initial condition *y*(0) = *y*0 ≠ 0, the solution $y(t)=y_{0}e^{at}$ tends toward the stationary point *y* = 0, but it only approaches it in the limit of infinite time, so the uniqueness of solutions over all finite times is guaranteed.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] By contrast for an equation in which the stationary point can be reached after a *finite* time, uniqueness of solutions does not hold.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] so the previous state of the system is not uniquely determined by its state at or after *t* = 0.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The uniqueness theorem does not apply because the derivative of the function *f* (*y*) = *y* ⁠2/3⁠ is not bounded in the neighborhood of *y* = 0 and therefore it is not Lipschitz continuous, violating the hypothesis of the theorem.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Let L be the Lipschitz constant of $(t,y)\mapsto f(t,y)$ with respect to $y.$ The function f is continuous as a function of $(t,y)$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] which is the supremum of (the absolute values of) the slopes of the function.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The function f attains a maximum on $C_{a,b}$ because f is continuous and $C_{a,b}$ is compact.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] To apply the Banach fixed-point theorem, we must show that $\Gamma$ maps a complete non-empty metric space *X* into itself and also is a contraction mapping.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] We first show that $\Gamma$ takes $B_{b}(y_{0})$ into itself in the space of continuous functions with the uniform norm.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Here, $B_{b}(y_{0})$ is a closed ball in the space of continuous (and bounded) functions "centered" at the constant function $y_{0}$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] where $t'$ is some number in $[t_{0}-a,t_{0}+a]$ where the maximum is achieved.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Now let us prove that $\Gamma$ is a contraction mapping as required to apply the Banach fixed-point theorem.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] We have established that the Picard's operator is a contraction on the Banach spaces with the metric induced by the uniform norm.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] This allows us to apply the Banach fixed-point theorem to conclude that the operator has a unique fixed point.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] We wish to remove the dependence of the interval *Ia* on *L*.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] To this end, there is a corollary of the Banach fixed-point theorem: if an operator *T**n* is a contraction for some *n* in **N**, then *T* has a unique fixed point.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] This inequality assures that for some large *m*, ${\frac {L^{m}\alpha ^{m}}{m!}}<1,$ and hence Γ*m* will be a contraction.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] So by the previous corollary Γ will have a unique fixed point.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Finally, we have been able to optimize the interval of the solution by taking *α* = min{*a*, ⁠*b*/*M*⁠}.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] In the end, this result shows the interval of definition of the solution does not depend on the Lipschitz constant of the field, but only on the interval of definition of the field and its maximum absolute value.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The Picard–Lindelöf theorem shows that the solution exists and that it is unique.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The Peano existence theorem shows only existence, not uniqueness, but it assumes only that *f* is continuous in y, instead of Lipschitz continuous.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] For example, the right-hand side of the equation ⁠*dy*/*dt*⁠ = *y* ⁠1/3⁠ with initial condition *y*(0) = 0 is continuous but not Lipschitz continuous.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Even more general is Carathéodory's existence theorem, which proves existence (in a more general sense) under weaker conditions on *f* .
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Although these conditions are only sufficient, there also exist necessary and sufficient conditions for the solution of an initial value problem to be unique, such as Okamura's theorem.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The Picard–Lindelöf theorem ensures that solutions to initial value problems exist uniquely within a local interval $[t_{0}-\varepsilon ,t_{0}+\varepsilon ]$ , possibly dependent on each solution.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] The behavior of solutions beyond this local interval can vary depending on the properties of *f* and the domain over which *f* is defined.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] For instance, if *f* is globally Lipschitz, then the local interval of existence of each solution can be extended to the entire real line and all the solutions are defined over the entire **R**.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] If *f* is only locally Lipschitz, some solutions may not be defined for certain values of *t*, even if *f* is smooth.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] For instance, the differential equation ⁠*dy*/*dt*⁠ = *y* 2 with initial condition *y*(0) = 1 has the solution *y*(*t*) = 1/(1-*t*), which is not defined at *t* = 1.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] Nevertheless, if *f* is a differentiable function defined on a compact submanifold of **R**n such that the prescribed derivative is tangent to the given submanifold, then the initial value problem has a unique solution for all time.
[src:differential-equations-ode/picard-lindelöf-theorem] More generally, in differential geometry: if *f* is a differentiable vector field defined over a domain which is a compact smooth manifold, then all its trajectories (integral curves) exist for all time.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] In mathematics, the **Wronskian** of n differentiable functions is the determinant of a matrix formed by the functions and their derivatives up to order $n-1$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] It was introduced in 1812 by the Polish mathematician Józef Wroński, and is used in the study of differential equations, where it can show the linear independence of certain sets of solutions.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] The Wrońskian of two differentiable functions f and g is $W(f,g)=fg'-gf'$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] This is the determinant of the matrix constructed by placing the functions in the first row, their first derivatives of the functions in the second row, and so on through the $(n-1)$ -st derivative, thus forming a square matrix.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] When the functions are solutions of a linear differential equation, the Wrońskian can be found explicitly using Abel's identity, even if the functions themselves are not known explicitly.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] If the functions are linearly dependent, then so are the columns of the Wrońskian (since differentiation is a linear operation), and the Wrońskian vanishes.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Thus, one may show that a set of differentiable functions is linearly independent on an interval by showing that their Wrońskian does not vanish identically.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] It may, however, vanish at isolated points.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] A common misconception is that $W=0$ everywhere implies linear dependence.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Peano (1889) pointed out that the functions *x*2 and |*x*|***·** x* have continuous derivatives and their Wrońskian vanishes everywhere, yet they are not linearly dependent in any neighborhood of 0.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] There are several extra conditions which combine with vanishing of the Wronskian in an interval to imply linear dependence.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Over fields of characteristic p the Wronskian may vanish even for linearly independent polynomials; for example, the Wronskian of $x^{p}$ and the constant function 1 is identically zero.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] In general, for an n th order linear differential equation, if $n-1$ solutions are known, the last one can be determined by using the Wronskian.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Consider the second order differential equation in Lagrange's notation: $y''=a(x)y'+b(x)y$ where $a(x)$ , $b(x)$ are known, and y is the unknown function to be found.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Therefore, the Wronskian obeys a simple first order differential equation and can be exactly solved: $W(x)=C~e^{A(x)}$ where $A'(x)=a(x)$ and C is a constant.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Now suppose that we know one of the solutions, say $y_{2}$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Then, by the definition of the Wrońskian, $y_{1}$ obeys a first order differential equation: $y'_{1}-{\frac {y'_{2}}{y_{2}}}y_{1}=-W(x)/y_{2}$ and can be solved exactly (at least in theory).
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] The method is easily generalized to higher order equations.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] The relationship between the Wronskian and linear independence can also be strengthened in the context of a differential equation.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Thus, counterexamples like $x^{2}$ and $x{|x|}$ (whose Wronskian is zero everywhere) or even $x^{2}$ and 1 (whose Wronskian $2x$ is zero somewhere) are ruled out; neither pair can consist of solutions to the same second-order differential equation of this type.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] (It's true that $x^{2}$ and 1 are both solutions to the same *third*-order differential equation $y^{(3)}=0$ .
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] For *n* functions of several variables, a **generalized Wronskian**is a determinant of an *n* by *n* matrix with entries *Di*(*fj*) (with 0 ≤ *i* < *n*), where each *Di* is some constant coefficient linear partial differential operator of order *i*.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] If the functions are linearly dependent then all generalized Wronskians vanish.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] As in the single variable case the converse is not true in general: if all generalized Wronskians vanish, this does not imply that the functions are linearly dependent.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] However, the converse is true in many special cases.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] For example, if the functions are polynomials and all generalized Wronskians vanish, then the functions are linearly dependent.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] Roth used this result about generalized Wronskians in his proof of Roth's theorem.
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] For more general conditions under which the converse is valid see Wolsson (1989b).
[src:differential-equations-ode/wronskian] The Wrońskian was introduced by Józef Hoene-Wroński (1812) and given its current name by Thomas Muir (1882, Chapter XVIII).
